2026-03-04 | Special Positions in a Binary Matrix

	Question
Given matrix mat, return the count of special positions.

	Approach
1.	Compute the number of 1s in every row.
2.	Compute the number of 1s in every column.
3.	Traverse the matrix again:
		If mat[i][j] == 1
		and rowCount[i] == 1
		and colCount[j] == 1
		then (i, j) is a special position.
4.	Increment the result.
5.	Time Complexity:
		O(m × n)
6.	Space Complexity:
		O(m + n)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    int numSpecial(vector<vector<int>>& mat) {
        int m = mat.size();
        int n = mat[0].size();

        vector<int> row(m, 0), col(n, 0);

        for (int i = 0; i < m; i++)
            for (int j = 0; j < n; j++)
                if (mat[i][j] == 1) {
                    row[i]++;
                    col[j]++;
                }

        int count = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < m; i++)
            for (int j = 0; j < n; j++)
                if (mat[i][j] == 1 && row[i] == 1 && col[j] == 1)
                    count++;

        return count;
    }
};

	Key Insight
A position is special only when its row and column
each contain exactly one '1'.
Precomputing row and column counts allows us to
check this condition efficiently in linear time.
